  customerText:
  - This used to belong to my father. It should still technically fit fine but, uh,
    well... you can see he did quite a number on it while he was still with us.
  - "This was passed onto me from my grandmama, and they would be so pretty if anyone
    else bothered to wash them, or care for them, or even remember them for that
    matter. Oh well, people nowadays don\u2019t respect clothes like they used to."
  - Here. With my old frame, it just don't stay on me right anymore, and they're
    also a bit beat up... okay, maybe more than a bit. But what can I say, these
    saw a lot of action in my heyday, and I want them to have a second chance.
  - Hey. I got this from my dad. I admit I kinda want to appreciate it. Problem is
    it looks like it went through a cement mixer filled with glass and obsidian pieces.
    I heard you actually know how to fix stuff, so I came by to see what's your deal.
    Anyways, here you go.
  - "Sup. You guy who fixes clothes and stuff? Check this out, found it in a charity
    shop and thought it would look good if I could get it into tip-top shape\u2026
    but, uhm, let\u2019s just say I, uhh, forgot that I\u2019m not that handy with
    needle thread, y\u2019know? Anyways thankyousomuchand byeee!"
  - "So, you\u2019re the one who has been fixing. Here, something for you bite on,
    since you don\u2019t look that busy and I doubt anyone else would want, or know,
    what to do with this."
  Sucessfulfeedback:
  - "Hmm\u2026 the quality of the stitches is pretty good, and the choice of using
    natural materials for the patches means that eventually it should all degrade
    away naturally, leaving nothing behind to destroy the environment. Of course
    this is only one part of the process, since as long as people throw away clothes
    so casually, and companies and corporations get away with cheaping out on the
    materials used, labour as well as keep encouraging people to be wasteful with
    their clothing then your work can only do so much. Nevertheless, Excellent work."
  UnSucessfulfeedback:
  - "Hmm\u2026 The craftsmanship looks good, but the material\u2026 for your information,
    clothes made and repaired with synthetic fabrics are exponentially more difficult,
    or in some cases even impossible, to reuse let alone recycle. Synthetic and blended
    textiles often contain PFAS and other chemicals that don\u2019t break down in
    the environment, and can accumulate in the land and inside of living organisms.
    Oh well, I do suppose failure is the forge of greatness, isn\u2019t it?"
